Why President Bush cannot be re-elected in America
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush jeopardizes the security of the United States and the world while simultaneously undermining American values.
On account of my opposition to him, I have been damned by Bush's election campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 with a campaign program that promised a foreign policy of "modesty."
If he is re-elected, this will be a mandate for President Bush's doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
In rejecting Bush's policy at the polls, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001 demanded a strong response.
They have, however, also led to the disabling of the critical process - the comprehensive and honest discussion of the impending problems - that is indispensable for democracy.
By declaring it unpatriotic, Bush has silenced the criticism.
For the duration of 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress any dissent.
This way, he has led America in the wrong direction.
By playing directly into Osama bin Laden's hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and al-Qaeda maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not justified.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy towards America erupted all over the world.
This has given way to widespread bitterness.
Far more people than on September 11 are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush likes to claim that the terrorists hate Americans for what they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Equally, the torture of inmates at Abu Ghraib prison was not the work of a few "bad apples."
She was part of a system for handling prisoners set up by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The world at large condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's security is in good hands with him by addressing the fears triggered by the September 11 attacks.
In times of danger, people rally around their flag, and Bush has exploited this by fostering a sense of vulnerability.
His campaign assumes that people are ultimately not interested in the truth and will almost believe anything if it's repeated often enough.
It can't be right with America if we fall for it.
For example, around 40% of Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein was involved in September 11, despite the 9/11 Commission - appointed by Bush and led by a Republican - having clearly established that no such connection existed.
Wake up, America.
Don't you realize we're being led astray?
The war in Iraq was based on false assumptions from start to finish - if it is to have an end.
It was a war of choice, not necessity.
More so, America went to war under a pretext: mass destruction weapons could not be found, and a connection to al-Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush claimed that America went to war to liberate Iraq.
Democracy cannot be imposed on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be relieved that they are rid of him.
America, however, had the duty to ensure law and order; instead, we witnessed Baghdad and other cities being plundered.
If we were truly concerned about the Iraqi people, we would have had to deploy a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would have had to protect not only the oil ministry, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they employed methods - such as breaking into private homes and mistreating prisoners - that outraged and humiliated the population, and thus sparked bitterness and anger.
The missteps and backpedaling of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the German source sentence is translated into English, taking into account the historical translation of "Amerika" as "America", and the translation style being consistent with the preceding texts.
First, the US attempted to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their assistance.
When the uprisings became unmanageable, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protégé with the reputation of a "strong man" - a far cry from a democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's election campaign team to gloss over the situation, the situation in Iraq remains bleak.
A large part of the western region was left to insurgents. Hopes for the conduct of free and fair elections in January are rapidly fading.
Civil war is looming.
Bush's war in Iraq has also inflicted immeasurable damage on America, weakened its military might, and undermined the morale of its troops.
Before the war, America could project the impression of overwhelming strength.
Not anymore.
Afghanistan is slipping out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed vigor.
One can criticize the Bush administration on many other political issues, but none are as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war have thus far approached nearly $200 billion and will continue to rise, as the invasion of Iraq proved to be much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush has taken a swipe at John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry replied that he would have done everything differently, and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But it will not be easy for him either, because America is stuck in a quagmire.
Leading military experts and diplomats had warned Bush repeatedly not to invade Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process by arguing that any criticism of the commander-in-chief would jeopardize US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should take a moment to pause and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection might prompt another question: Does Bush's cowboy demeanor qualify him to remain America's commander-in-chief?
